{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"afbcec17-be1c-44e5-86fa-860f187ced35","content":"`JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` is available out of the box in .NET 11. Here's the full program:\n\n```csharp\nusing System.Text.Json;\n\nvar person = new Person(\"Alice\", 30);\n\nvar options = new JsonSerializerOptions\n{\n    PropertyNamingPolicy = JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase,\n    WriteIndented = true\n};\n\nstring json = JsonSerializer.Serialize(person, options);\nConsole.WriteLine(json);\n\npublic record Person(string name, int age);\n```\n\n**Output:**\n```json\n{\n  \"Name\": \"Alice\",\n  \"Age\": 30\n}\n```\n\nThe record's lowercase positional parameters (`name`, `age`) generate lowercase properties, but `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` — new in .NET 11 — converts them to `Name` and `Age` in the JSON output. No custom naming policy class needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"835e84c4-2bb4-4a1f-aba7-e60f48f89672","outputTokens":222,"requestId":"4828:3BF41F:134B0CE:158AC4D:6A027965"},"id":"9a25c177-5bc3-408e-aaf5-54f27db337cf","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:50:50.685Z","parentId":"9ec3e248-2df8-43ef-a6ba-c5a74877c1c9"}
